<TD>
<IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/icons/icon1.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="ABSCENTER">
<FONT SIZE="1" color="#000000" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
posted December 08, 2001 08:18 AM &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=get_profile&u=00000675" target=_blank>
<IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/profile_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Profile for i3ullseye"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://" target=_new><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/homepage.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Author's Homepage"></A> &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=private_message&u=00000675"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/priv_message.gif" BORDER='0' ALT="Send New Private Message"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=edit_post&f=21&t=000214&reply_num=000000&u=00000675"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/edit_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Edit/Delete Post"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=reply&f=21&t=000214&replyto=000000"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/quote_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Reply With Quote"></A>
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#12350C">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
A few questions were asked of us, most soecifically we were asked if any spell line was seen as deficient. I am posting a copy of my report here since this actually has a much wider impact than just items on Test.<P>Focus is being turned on spells. This is a quick breakdown of the spells as is, and a basic description of what they do.<P>Sorceror Spells<P>Base Matter (Core Matters)<BR>Ward Blow (AF Buff) +Single Blade-Turn :Just a basic defensive Buff, and included in this line is one blade turning spell at level 19.<BR>Acid/Corrosive DOT: This is a 4 tick DOT that lasts 24 seconds.<P>Advanced Matter (Telekinesis)<BR>Forces DOT: This is a DOT that lasts 24 seconds and does damage 6 times (once every 4 seconds)<BR>Dex  Debuff: This drains the targets dexterity. The effect is minimal most times.<P>Base Body (Body Destruction)<BR>Life Drain/Consumption: Basic life transfer. Costs more power and is less efficient than straight direct damage spells.<BR>Strength  Debuff: Lowers the targets strength. Can sometimes see a noticable drop in damage done by the MOB.<BR>Snare/Root: Slows the target to 1%, then they slowly move faster after the fact. Damage breaks this instantly.<P>Advanced Body (Disorientation)<BR>Direct Damage: More efficient than the life drains as far as power spent and damage done.<BR>Dexterity/Quickness Debuff: Drains both stats from the target. The effect again is not readily apparent many times.<BR>Area Effect Root/Snare: Nice upgrade to the base snare, but this one has a small area of effect.<P>Base Mind (Mind Twisting)<BR>Confusion: Target will attack random enemies, and sometimes even allies. Only works on NPCs so limited RvR use.<BR>Mesmerize: Immobilizes the target completely. Can not be cast on a target after it takes a small amount of damage.<BR>Run Speed Buff: Movement rate of all in your group is increased, but does not work on our pets.<BR>Amnesia: Wipes the targets agro list. They do NOT however forget you, so they come immediately for you after you cast this. Useless for PvP, but the casting itself does qualify as a spell cast to interrupt the target.<P>Advanced Mind (Domination)<BR>Charm: Can get up to even level pets if the spell is kept current. Some levels, and many areas, are severely lacking in Charmable MOBs. Though it says humanoids are the target, many MANY creatures are technically humanoid and can not be charmed.<BR>AE Mesmerize: Upgrade to the base Mez, with a decent area effect added.<BR>Strength and Constitution Debuff: The most noticeable and potent debuff in our arsenal. Since many Sorcerors spec MIND high, this stays effective longer than the other debuffs, and helps when hunting with your pet to keep them from taking too much damage.<P>Now on to the analysis.:<P>Areas for improvement to what exists.<P>Just focusing on what IS in place and how it could be improved.<P>First the run spell needs to work on the pet. This has been broken for far too long. Maybe making it a single target spell with a 10 minute duration would better for this. It would also allow it to get away from being a song, which is totally out of place.<P>Next would be our charms. Plain and simple, we need to be able to charm more targets. Many elemental types cannot be charmed. Nor can smaller giant types (Ogres and Ettins). Seems if ANY other classification could be applied, it takes precedence and makes the MOB no longer humanoid. If it has arms and legs, and can speak a spoken language, we should be able to charm it.<P>Clarify how amnesia should work, and if it is not working as intended fix it. Right now all agro is wiped, but the list is not cleared and the MOB still comes straight for you. If they are supposed to forget their entire list, lets get it fixed.<P>The debuffs need to have more tangible effect. Maybe instead of increasing how much they debuff, a secondary effect could be added to them for substance. <P>And lastly the blade turn. Very nice addition to casters, and very needed. But sorcerors seem to have lower hit points than many other casters. We are far less survivable than the casters in Hibernia who can wear armor. And the other casters who fulfill our role get heavier armor or healing, and in at least one case both. So perhaps our blade turn should be a Karmic Repurcussion. Half the damage that would have been done to us could be reflected back at the attacker.<P><BR>Areas for addition to what exists.<P>Ok, now plenty of new twists on our spells could help immensely in PvP. But the one area that just screams for attention is the Matter line. As it stands there are 2 basic spells in the base line (lumping the single blade turn spell with the other AF buffs as a defensive spell). There is the defensive line, and the basic DOT. The advanced spec of matter adds a new DOT (which adds nothing on top of the original, but replaces it) and a Snare spell…which the DOTs themselves nullify.<P>So the only way to make your advanced DOT worth using is to spec very heavily in matter. This makes you then use the advanced DOT instead of the basic, rendering these lines basically the same. You cast one or the other depending on levels, so it is in effect one spell based on the matter skill. Topping that off, once you HAVE opted to use the higher DOT, and focused your training on Matter, now the second benefit, the Snare/Root spell, is nullified when you use the other primary spell in the line, the DOT.<P>There needs to be more here.<P>Of all the areas that seem to be neglected, Matter is by far the least chosen spec path. Not that many choose body either. Our Mind spec is strong, and really defines the class. Body adds a DD and a nice single target root, so is quite capable for solo play. Matter is the one line that fails.<P>Suggestions:<P>As mentioned earlier, maybe a spell that reflects the damage taken back upon the attacker. This could be combined with a blade turn type buff, or become it’s own buff layered on top of the others. <P>Perhaps following the idea of telekinesis, a force based spell to push targets back would be effective. Maybe a physical wall of force, or a bubble shield effect.<P>A levitation spell would be EXCELLENT in this line, and could alleviate all that horrible falling damage. If this is a group spell it would allow us to aid a group in crossing moats and other waterways quickly for PvP. This would be a great addition to battlefield strategy.<P>There are many more suggestions to be made, and many more good ideas out there. But the matter line is definitely in need of SOME sort of attention. A few key things to keep in mind, do NOT add things to the advanced path that would nullify the use of one in the basic path. There are already 2 DOTs and a Snare/Root that basically equate to ONE spell you can cast at a given time. You must ensure that the higher spec spell can complement the character, and actually add some functionality. Improving on how well a particular effect works should be left a matter of level.<P>The general community if furious at this point. The frustration level is high. Sorcerors were fairly rare to begin with, not that many groups can not rely on their Mez to be quite as effective in groups, they are getting less group invites. Not only have we always been weak in PvP (relatively) we now may have less Sorcerors actually making it to high enough level to even consider PvP. Many choose the sorcerer with the idea that we will be the best in crowd control and that is our niche. As sweeping changes are made to class abilities as a whole, it is becoming apparent that we are NOT necessarily the best at Crowd Control, and these changes actually do not address the initial imbalances they were intended for, but only weaken the other classes grouped into the category affected by the change.<P>If by beefing up the matter line you could add more group and PvP functionality, it could go a long way toward bringing the sorcerer back up to the standards everyone has come to expect from the class.<P>--------------------<P>i3ullseye<BR>"You're good, but me? I'm Magic!"<P>Rictus -Sorceror(DAOC)/Rictus(EQ)<BR>DAOC Sorceror team lead...
</FONT>
